What Colonel O'Kelly refers to, as the barbarous treatment inflicted upon the Irish gar- rison after their surrender, is thus spoken of in King James's Memoirs, and by Doctor Charles Leslie.

The former authority says, that they “ found little compassion at the Enemies hands, who amongst other cruel mages, were so inhumain as to refuse to bury those who through misery dyed in prison, till they amounted to 30 or 40 at a time through a seeming neglect, or to saue trouble, but in reality that the infection of the dead and corrupting bodys might poison and destroy the rest.''
